results.notes:
The sole image in the Paul Stamets book and every image I could find on the internet based on this species (even just scrolling though google images) looks extremely similar, in my opinion, the same.
However this excerpt sticks out from page 116 of the afore mentioned book:

Under “Stem:” – “…to a fairly persistent superior densely fibrillose to membranous annulus that develops from a thickly cortinate partial veil.” And from the next page under “Comments:” – “It also bears similarity to Psilocybe semilanceata, except for the superior, persistent, and often membranous annulus that can be bluish toned.”

This (Annulus) is the only thing that would place a doubt, except from the fact the I cannot find any other reference to an annulus on the Fimetaria, anywhere else. And I have looked a lot. I have seen plenty of partial veils on the younger specimens and have included some in this observation (and in the bonus imgur gallery). So because I can’t find any other reference to the annulus, apart from this book, it then removes the doubt.

Everything else is fully consistent, very thick seprable gelatinous pellicle; hygrophanous; undulating stem; sometimes undulating cap (from slight to noticeable); prominent umbo; chalk white stem that discolours to honey brown with handling; stem equal to slightly swollen at base; blueish mycelium attached to base of stem; from Stamets’ book: “…and sometimes with grayish bluish green tones.” and “Surface covered with with whitish fibrillose patches”.

The bruising effect is quite rare, I have collected a large amount of this species (well over 100, probably just over 200 and observed much more than collected) and only observed prominent bruising in around 3 specimens. I have noticed very slight bruising in closer to every 1 out of 8, maybe 1 out of 12. But the mycelium at the base being very slight light blue is much more common.
And when I say prominent bruising I mean very blue/greenish (like Stamets described) But the bruising seems to be more rare than it is in Semilanceata.

Final note: I would prefer to put “Looks promising” on this post, but as it is my post, I would rather keep my vote in the middle and wait for further opinion and weigh-ins based on the descriptions provided. (Also happy to elaborate further or answer specifics if asked.)

Not sure if this is allowed here, but this is an Imgur gallery I put together from the most useful images I’ve taken, with little descriptions. (I will be updating this in the next week with a few more pics) – https://imgur.com/gallery/2BE9Y5b

Bountiful apologies for the many words, but I would like to be thorough with this.

Cheers!
